This is what I mean:<p><pre><code>  var results = [0,0,0,0,0,0];
  for (var i = 0; i < 6000000; i += 1) {
    results[Math.floor((Math.random() * 6))] += 1;
  }
  console.log(results);
</code></pre>
The results are:<p><pre><code>  [1002140, 999355, 1000009, 1000401, 1000014, 998081]
</code></pre>
Basically, they are all within 1% tolerance of each number getting 1 million occurrences.<p>So when you look at the clumping on random dots on a screen, given a large enough sample size, I would anticipate that the probability of keeping a clumped visual distribution would become quite improbable.
